WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.360
Hi, I'm Hannah, and I'm here to talk to you about expectations on your data. Because as

00:00:06.360 --> 00:00:12.480
data scientists, we are often not the ones collecting it, we're just given access to

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:18.120
it, and then we build something with it. Maybe a dashboard, maybe a prediction model. And

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:26.000
sometimes, sometimes things change. And if a column gets renamed, things wreck. And if

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.840
a variable gets recorded in a different unit, things might now be silently garbage. Wouldn't

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:39.200
it be nicer to just get a heads up, an email that says these things are changing, rather

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:47.520
than the dashboard is broken. You may want to get that email from a colleague, but if

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:52.400
that's not possible, you can also run regular validation checks and have a system email

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:59.080
you. And that's what pointblank is for. It's feature rich, it's got loads of documentation,

00:00:59.080 --> 00:01:04.599
and my goal here is just to give you a sense of what's possible and how to get started.

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:10.160
The main thing you get from pointblank is a beautiful HTML table like this. You can

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:16.199
stick it in a report, or you can have it emailed to you. And roughly one row is one validation

00:01:16.199 --> 00:01:22.199
role. The specifications are to the left, and the results are to the right. So, if you're

00:01:22.199 --> 00:01:27.839
validating the contents of a particular column, that's the rows, those are the units. It will

00:01:27.839 --> 00:01:33.959
tell you how many and how many passed and how many failed. And life is messy, and your

00:01:33.959 --> 00:01:41.360
data might be too. But in both cases, you can typically tolerate some amount of that.

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:50.919
So pointblank lets you specify thresholds for when you want to warn, stop, or be notified.

00:01:50.919 --> 00:01:56.199
And if you specify that, at minimum, it drives the colors to the left of that table. But

00:01:56.199 --> 00:02:00.239
really, it can do a lot more, because it can trigger any action that you can express in

00:02:00.239 --> 00:02:07.239
R code. And lastly, that column to the right is for when things go wrong. You can get access

00:02:07.239 --> 00:02:13.960
to a CSV with the units or rows that failed that condition. And the core code pattern

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:19.880
of the package is something you might have seen elsewhere, for example, in header recipes.

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:26.979
It is simply create the core object, add specifications to it, and then apply those specifications

00:02:26.979 --> 00:02:36.520
to the data. That data can be local in your session, or remote in a database. And there's

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:42.080
a lot of pre-made validation functions for you. So you can stick together your validation

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:49.399
plan as it is necessary for your data set. But I promised you some action based on these

00:02:49.399 --> 00:02:55.320
thresholds. So how to specify them? Well, there's an action argument. It takes the result

00:02:55.320 --> 00:03:02.919
of an action levels function, which lets you specify these three thresholds. It can be

00:03:02.919 --> 00:03:08.339
an absolute threshold, a relative threshold, and the set of functions you want executed

00:03:08.339 --> 00:03:15.479
at a particular threshold. So here, we just warn when we hit the warning threshold. Not

00:03:15.479 --> 00:03:23.039
particularly exciting, but you get the idea. You can specify that in sort of the overall

00:03:23.039 --> 00:03:29.880
object and then it applies to all of the validation rules you might add. Or if you want to fine

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:35.479
tune out and have a different threshold for a particularly important validation rule,

00:03:35.479 --> 00:03:45.320
you can specify there, too. It takes the same actions argument. And you can have an action

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:52.399
or just sort of arbitrary R code carried out at the end of the validation in the ends functions

00:03:52.399 --> 00:04:02.080
argument. You could, for example, add your email notification there. And because if it

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:05.759
emails you every single time a validation runs and everything's okay, that might be

00:04:05.759 --> 00:04:14.580
a little spammy. The default is to only send that email when you hit the notify threshold.

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:22.119
But that's just a feature of that email function, not that that applies to all of the code you

00:04:22.119 --> 00:04:29.119
would execute in this little block. So sometimes the table is beautiful, but not enough, and you

00:04:29.119 --> 00:04:34.480
want to be able to program against it. So HonkBlack lets you do that, too, with a set of functions

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:41.559
that let you access the results of the validation. And the place to find more info is this. Thank you.

